node.text:
What do the new #WonderWoman1984 movie and the @Smithsonian have in common? 

(Feel free to keep scrolling, no spoilers ahead).

Director Patty Jenkins talks about the connection between the two in an interview with us. For those that already saw #WW84, well, you may already have an idea.

node.title: 'Wonder Woman 1984' Director Patty Jenkins Interview with the Smithsonian

node.title: Perseverance Rover Landing Site with John Grant

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Air and Space Museum on August 19, 2021. May be an image of airplane.

node.text:
Today we celebrate National Aviation Day! ✈ 

We’d like to hear about some of your favorite aircraft in our collection. Let us know your thoughts by dropping some comments below!

node.accessibility_caption: Small blue, white, and red aircraft

node.text: A flying chipmunk 🐿 This De Havilland Chipmunk "Pennzoil Special" was flown by veteran aerobatic and movie pilot Art Scholl in airshows around the country in the 70s and early 80s. He acquired the aircraft in 1968 and made a number of modifications to suit his purposes, giving it a shorter wingspan and larger vertical fin and rudder.  At airshows, Scholl often flew with his dog Aileron, who rode the wing as Scholl taxied on the runway or sat on his shoulder in the aircraft. Following Scholl's death, his estate donated "Pennzoil Special" to the Museum, and it was delivered on this day in 1987. #AirSpacePhoto

node.accessibility_caption: Concept image of Mars and its two moons Phobos and Deimos.

node.text: It's only fitting that the planet named for the Roman god of war (Mars) has moons named for the personification of fear (Phobos) and terror (Deimos). On this day in 1877, astronomer Asaph Hall discovered Phobos, the larger of Mars' two moons.

node.accessibility_caption: Man jumping out of high altitude gondola. Clouds can be seen below him.

node.text:
Excelsior! On this day in 1960, U.S. Air Force Capt. Joseph Kittinger made a record-setting high altitude parachute jump from his Excelsior III balloon-supported gondola at an altitude of 31,333 meters (102,800 feet). During his "long lonely leap" he was in free fall for 4 minutes and 36 second, reaching speeds up to 614 mph. He opened his parachute at 5,334 meters (17,500 feet). His jump set the record for the highest parachute jump, which stood for over 50 years. Visit the link in our bio to read the blog.
📷: U.S. Air Force

node.accessibility_caption: Black and shite image of large crowd gathered on a street holding signs that reads "peace".

node.text:
Victory in the Pacific.

Today in 1945, Japanese Emperor Hirohito announced the Japanese government’s surrender in a radio address to the empire. World War II in the Pacific had come to an end.

📷: "American servicemen and women gather in front of "Rainbow Corner" Red Cross club in Paris to celebrate the unconditional surrender of the Japanese." National Archives, Records of the Office of the Chief Signal Officer. (111-SC-210241)

node.accessibility_caption: View of the ring system surrounding the planet Uranus.

node.text:
A once every 42 years type of 📸

Using the onboard Wide Field Planetary Camera 2, the Hubble Space Telescope captured this rare edge-on view of the ring system of the planet Uranus, on this day in 2007. Astronomers on Earth can only see the rings' edge every 42 years due to the planet's 84 year orbit. In fact, the last time the rings were tilted edge-on to Earth, astronomers didn't even know they existed.

node.accessibility_caption: Apollo 11 astronauts standing on the back of a vehicle as they make their way through a large crowd at a parade in 1969.

node.text:
A heroes’ welcome.

On August 13, 1969, the Apollo 11 astronauts were given a heroes' welcome in New York City with a ticker-tape parade through the Canyon of Heroes. It was reported that a record tonnage of paper was dropped by enthusiastic citizens during the parade.

On the same day, the astronauts received the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor.

node.accessibility_caption: Apollo 11 astronauts standing on the back of a vehicle as they make their way through a large crowd at a parade in 1969.
A black and white image of Apollo 11 astronauts receiving the Presidential Medal of Freedom in front of an audience.
Space shuttle just after separating from a 747. Both fly over the clouds and against a blue sky.

node.text:
Fly free, Enterprise.
On this day in 1977, Space Shuttle Enterprise, crewed by astronauts Fred Haise and Gordon Fullerton, made its first free flight from a 747 during Shuttle Approach & Landing Tests. This NASA photo was taken soon after Enterprise and the 747 Shuttle Carrier Aircraft separated for the free flight and Enterprise's glide landing.

node.accessibility_caption: Gold half-dome canister with instrumentation inside exposed

node.text:
To space and back again.
This Discoverer XIII reentry capsule was the first human-made object to be recovered from orbit. "Discoverer" was the cover name for the highly classified Air Force/CIA Corona photoreconnaissance satellite program.
It was recovered north of Hawaii by the U.S. Navy on this day in 1960, one day after it was launched from Vandenberg Air Force Base. While the Discoverer XIII satellite did not carry cameras or film, and the capsule contained only diagnostic instruments, other Corona satellites carried cameras and film beginning with Discoverer XIV one week later. By the end of the Corona program in May 1972, over 120 Corona satellites had successfully flown and photographed the Soviet Union, China, and other nations. #AirSpacePhoto

node.accessibility_caption: 1903 Wright Flyer on display in the Arts & Industries Building, circa 1950s.

node.text:
Even before we had a building of our own, Air and Space artifacts had a home on the National Mall in Washington, DC.

Aircraft like the 1903 Wright Flyer, Lockheed Vega Winnie Mae, and the Spirit of St. Louis were on display at the Smithsonian’s Arts & Industries Building before finding their permanent homes at our flagship building on the National Mall. #Smithsonian175

Winnie Mae airplane hanging from the ceiling in a room.
Airplane hanging from the ceiling in the middle of a large room.
Seven research aircraft arranged on tarmac for a photo

node.text: "Okay, everyone squeeze in!" 📸 This photo from August 1953 shows a selection of research aircraft at the NACA High-Speed Flight Research Station. How many of them can you identify?

node.accessibility_caption: White biplane with Olympic Rings painted on its tail

node.text:
Did you know that in 1936, Aeronautics was an Olympic event? 🥇✈️
Switzerland’s Hermann Schreiber was awarded an Olympic gold medal for merit in Aeronautics for a glider flight that took place over the Alps in 1935! And there were plenty of actual aeronautical feats to witness at the Berlin games. The Hindenburg hovered in the skies over the Olympic stadium, painted with the Olympic rings. The first public demonstration of the Messerschmitt Bf 109 prototype took place. And the Museum's Bücker Bü-133C Jungmeister was there too! 
Captain Alexander Papana of the Rumanian Air Force had placed fourth in the two-man bobsled event in the 1932 Lake Placid Olympics and had won the gold medal in the 1933 World Championships. Papana participated in the Olympics aeronautics demonstrations in 1936 and his Bücker Bü-133C Jungmeister, pictured here, featured Olympic rings on its tail. #Olympics
